    <!-- Translation notes -->
    <h3>Translation notes</h3>
    <p>The blog post defines free monoids via a universal construction in the category <strong>Mon</strong> of monoids, using the forgetful functor <code>U : Mon -> Set</code> and ranking candidates by the existence of unique homomorphisms. This page skips the categorical machinery and works directly with lists and fold. The key correspondence: Haskell's <code>foldMap :: Monoid m => (a -> m) -> [a] -> m</code> is the concrete implementation of the universal homomorphism. Give it a function from generators to any monoid, and it produces the unique structure-preserving map. The blog post also discusses how every monoid is a quotient of a free monoid. This page illustrates that with mod-3 arithmetic, but the full picture involves equivalence relations on the free monoid that are compatible with concatenation (i.e., congruences).</p>

